146.1: Save! It's the Wise Thing to Do!
146.2: This game uses autosave features. Data will automatically save after certain points in the game such as at the end of event scenarios. You can also save manually from the Pause Menu or at the save points found inside safe rooms in certain areas of the city. Keep in mind that you cannot save during event scenarios and battles. Saving will record your current progress up to that point, which you will be able to resume by selecting Continue from the title screen.

147.2: You will find an Item Box in your hideout and also throughout the game's various dungeons. Accessing these boxes will allow you to store or take out any of the items you own.

148.2: Accessing the closet on the 2nd floor of Survive Bar will cause time to shift. Use this to your advantage any time you need to visit places only accessible at night or meet people who only come out during the day.

149.2: Various parked taxis will allow you to travel around the city at warp-speed. You can even do this via the Pause Menu. Be aware, however, that rides aren't free and convenience comes at a price.

150.2: The mini map is displayed in the lower-left corner, showing your surroundings, points of interest, and enemies. Just press <symbol=button_touchpad> to display the entire map, which you can create waypoint markers on! Use both maps to figure out where you're headed and how to get there!

151.1: You'll Be Running Marathons in No Time!
151.2: Pressing <symbol=button_batsu> or <symbol=button_r2> while walking will cause you to sprint!

152.2: Pressing <symbol=button_l3> will put you in first-person mode, allowing you to move around and see the city through Kasuga's eyes. Just know that the perspective will revert to third-person during battles and conversations.

154.2: You will obtain various Valuables throughout the game. You can take time to appreciate them by accessing Items from the Pause Menu. Valuables may neither be discarded nor sold.

156.2: Changing jobs at Hello Work will allow you to change your appearance in accordance with a given job. Also, upon clearing the game, you will be able to wear your job outfits at all times, not just in battle.

157.2: You will be able to explore the world beyond the game's final chapter in Premium Adventure. During Premium Adventure, all progress made up until the moment you cleared the game will carry over. Try things on higher difficulties that can only be accessed in Premium Adventure and strive for 100% completion!

158.2: You will be able to assign jobs to Kasuga and his party members at Hello Work. There are special attacks and skills unique to each job, so choose the jobs best suited to the situation at hand. Training in various jobs will improve Kasuga and his party members' overall status and abilities as well, so try them all and take our heroes to the next level!

159.2: Kasuga will befriend many allies throughout his adventure, and up to three of them can join him around town or in battle. Kasuga cannot be removed as the party's leader. You may choose who will accompany him by accessing Party from the Pause Menu.

160.2: You can equip Kasuga and his fellow party members with a wide variety of gear. Each piece of gear has different status boosts and effects, so be sure to try them all out and see which gear best fits each party member.

1.1: The new Soji model is complete!
1.2: Thanks to your investment, development of the new Soji model was a success! I want you to be the first user. Meet me in front of Jinnai Station!

1.2: You can eat and drink at eating establishments. Indulging in this fashion will not only restore lost health, but also give you experience points. Certain combinations of items ordered will net you bonus experience points, so don't be afraid to mix and match! As the saying goes, "A good conscience is a continual feast."

2.2: In case you haven't noticed, consuming too much alcohol will get you drunk. The more booze you drink, the drunker you'll get. Sober up by drinking water or waiting for it to wear off. There are three levels of drunkenness and at its highest, you may end up attacking your party members in battle. The attack power for certain skills may also go up when you're drunk. As the saying goes, "A man's true character comes out when he's drunk."

3.2: You will be able to deposit your money via an ATM at Convenience Stores. Anything stored away will be safe and sound even upon being eliminated in battle. As the saying goes, "He who will not economize will have to agonize."

4.2: You can sell everything except for Valuables at Pawn Shops. If you need immediate funds, selling off items you don't need there would be the quickest way. As the saying goes, "When somebody says it's not about the money, it's about the money."

6.1: Craft with Romance at the Workshop!
6.2: You will be able to craft and enhance weapons and gear at the Romance Workshop. By scavenging the streets for materials and investing in the workshop's facility, you will be able to craft a wider variety of gear. Be aggressive in utilizing the workshop to improve your arsenal! As the saying goes, "Iron sharpens iron."

7.2: Dining at certain restaurants around Yokohama with your friends and ordering certain combinations of menu items will allow you to see what's called Table Talk unfold. The bond between you and participating party members will deepen, so be sure to try everything on the menu when you walk into a new restaurant with them!

8.2: Ordering a certain combination of menu items can trigger a Combo Meal. When this happens, you and your party will gain a perk, such as temporary stat boosts, increased money or EXP gained from battle, or other benefits. So get creative and order some delicious combos.

1.2: While strolling around town, you can collect CDs which you can listen to at Survive Bar.

2.2:
You can take up a hobby of raising plants and crafting bouquets, bentos and medicines from Master at Survive Bar.

Mishmash Lunch Box - 2 potato & 2 tomato.

Packed Luch Box - 2 onion & 2 daikon.

Chilled Noodles - 5 hot pepper, 2 garlic & 2 daikon.

Homestyle Lunch Box - 4 tomato, 3 daikon, 3 onion, 4 potato.

Special Lunch Box - 4 potato, 4 garlic, 4 onion, 1 carrot.

Luxury Kiwami Lunch Box - 10 garlic, 10 hot pepper, 5 mushrooms, 3 fruits, 2 carrots.

Restorative Medicine - 10 leafs, 5 mushrooms.

Comforting Medicine - 10 leafs,5 fruits.

Restorative Bolus - 15 fruits, 2 carrots, 3 lilies

Revival Bolus - 20 mushrooms, 5 carrots, 3 roses.

Ressurection Bolus - 20 fruits, 15 leafs, 10 carrots, 3 pine trees.

For bouquets, you need 9 pine trees, 10 roses, 12 lilies and 15 pansies for each.

4.2: You can find items by checking specific locations such as vending machines. If you find an area where the ground has a shining circle, approach it and try pressing <symbol=button_shikaku>.

5.2: There are locked gold and silver safes throughout the city. A gold safe is opened with a single gold key. Silver safes can all be opened once you acquire a "Silver Safe Skeleton Key." Gold safes tend to have rarer items, so keep your eyes peeled for them!

6.2: In the city you may come across abandoned briefcases which contain useful items. Gain access to their contents by actively (but nonchalantly) opening them.

7.2: At times, you may encounter and capture insects resting on trees. Not only can you sell the rarer ones at a high price, some of them may prove useful in weapon creation. Try to catch them!

8.2: Fulfill requests and rid the city of its social ills. A quest might be anything from taking down thugs to searching for missing persons. When you fulfill a request and report to one of many available reps, you will receive your due reward. Your rank will increase as you fulfill requests, allowing you to take on more advanced ones. Requests are automatically undertaken, so make sure to periodically check these from the Pause Menu.

9.2: Challenges are quests that hone one's humanity, as befits a noble hero. Fulfilling these will help develop Kasuga's Personality. The details of the quests can be checked under "Part-time Hero" in the Pause Menu. Completing one challenge will unlock another, so do your heroic best to vanquish them all!

2.2:
Vocational Schools specialize in improving Personality. By passing exams and obtaining licenses, Kasuga can significantly improve his personality parameters.

*You will be required to pay an exam fee for each license exam. Speak to the receptionist at Ounabara Vocational School if you wish to take license exams.

3.2:
Need help pounding your enemies? You can call Poundmates for a fee from your smartphone via "Etc." from the battle menu. The roster will grow as you progress through the main story or clear substories.

Each Poundmate has a powerful ability at a premium cost and are ranked by increasing order of bronze, silver, or gold, with each tier being more powerful and more costly than the former. Some of them will have certain conditions and restrictions, like not being able to help out at night. Plan your strategy accordingly with these factors in mind.

4.2:
This popular attraction will have you speeding around the streets of Yokohama in a thrilling race.

Feel the wind on these karts mounted with custom-designed engines as you hinder your opponents with attacks. But watch out—your opponents can attack you, too, and sustaining too much damage will immobilize you for a period of time. Picking up items during the race and using them wisely will surely help.

Your kart will have standard specs when starting out, but customization will become available with progress. Check it out near the ship in Hamakita Park when you feel the need for speed.

5.2:
You can listen in on short conversations that happen among your party members around the city. Listen until the end, and you'll strengthen the bond between you and your party members. 

Interrupting these conversations by opening menus or triggering a battle will not only force everyone to stop talking, but it's also just plain rude. If you speak to Iroha at Survive, you can listen to the conversations you've already had.

6.2: Interacting with a party member will fill your Bond Gauge with them. Fill it up a certain amount, and you will trigger a Drink Link. Learning about your party members' secret pasts or grievances will further deepen your bonds with them. Strong bonds can give excellent status boosts in battle, so it never hurts to be a friend.

7.2: Kasuga's personality is comprised of six unique facets: Passion, Confidence, Kindness, Charisma, Intellect, and Style. These can be developed by making correct or clever decisions during substories. Certain events and jobs require Kasuga's personality to be at a specific level in order to occur. Furthermore, there are other merits such as increasing his defense against the infliction of status ailments, so do your best to make our hero the best he can be!

8.2: The flowers you grow can be taken to the bartender at Survive to be arranged into bouquets. You can then give these bouquets to the different love interests Kasuga meets along his journey to deepen your bonds with them. Who knows? You just might see some sparks fly.

9.2:
If you're really serious about collecting cans, you can use boost to ram into your rivals and take theirs.
Check your surroundings, chug an energy drink, and get crashing!

1.2:
Glad you've been keeping up with your Sujidex. In fact, I'd like to give you a little something as a reward. Stop by the Sujimon Center when you can. It's on the second floor of that building off Sakura Lane, conveniently marked by a Sujimon icon on your map.

Your Sujimon Sensei

2.1: Way to keep on those Sujimon!
2.2:
Looks like you've taken your Sujimon collection to the next level. You have my thanks for registering so many of them. I'd like to give you something as a token of my appreciation. Stop by the Sujimon Center when you can. 

Your Sujimon Sensei

3.2:
Been a while, hasn't it? Sujimon Sensei here. Looks like there's just one entry left in your Sujidex. A truly amazing feat. I'd like to honor your accomplishment. Please come to my office at the Sujimon Center. I'll be waiting for you. 

Your Sujimon Sensei

1.2: If you successfully press the inputs displayed at the moment of your skill attack on an enemy, you will inflict more damage. This applies even when Autobattle is active. <symbol=button_shikaku> is used for consecutive inputs, while <symbol=button_sankaku> is used for timing inputs.

2.2: If you successfully press <symbol=button_cancel> at the moment you are attacked by the enemy, you will lessen the damage received. This applies even when Autobattle is active.

3.2: If Kasuga is in an area where his smartphone does not receive a signal, he cannot use Poundmates to call for help. Keep in mind some enemies emit signal-blocking waves that render smartphones useless.

4.2: Enemies may sideline and obstruct your regular attacks when you try to get past them, especially if you have party members who are being targeted. However, enemies cannot block skills.

5.1: When The Enemy Steals Your Items
5.2: Any items stolen from Kasuga or his party by enemies can be reclaimed by defeating them and winning the battle. However, you cannot reclaim stolen items once the enemy flees the battle.

6.2: If one party member knocks down an enemy and another party member is nearby, the latter may follow up with a chain attack. The likelihood of a chain attack depends on your bond with your party.

7.2: Status effects makes the characters behave in a certain way or change their stat temporarily during fight. Status effects wear off after some turns but can also be removed with the right items or skills.

8.2: After you attack, you may follow up with another if there happen to be objects like signs, bicycles, or furniture nearby. Kasuga in particular tends to use these objects to inflict a lot of damage to enemies.

9.2: An enemy who is knocked back might be struck by vehicle traffic, causing grave injury. In fact, depending on the environment, several different effects may occur when an enemy is knocked back, such as hitting and damaging other enemies who are in the way!

10.2: A battle begins when you encounter enemies roaming the streets. Losing these battles will not result in game over, but you will lose half your money.

11.2: A battle is lost if Kasuga is knocked out. Losing battles which occur from random encounters in the city will result in the loss of half your money. Other battles, however, will give you the choice to retry or return to the title screen.

12.2: The chance of knocking back an enemy depends on the difference between the attacking character's level and that of the target. If a character's level is lower than the target's, the chances of a knock back are low. Likewise, chances are high if the character's level is higher than the target's. Watch out when you challenge people who are more than 5 levels above you!

13.2: Drunk characters will do actions that are unpredictable. Either they will hit an ally, an enemy or remain in control.

14.2: Silence temporarily removes a character's ability to use skills.

15.2: Charmed characters will not attack until the charm wear offs. They can snap out of it if they get attacked.

16.2: Makes a character only use standard attacks on the person who enraged them. They may also block attacks directed at other party members.

17.2: Characters who are brainwashed attack allies.

24.2:

25.2:

Resistances - rage, fear and sleep.

26.2:
Saeko's inherent boldness and experience as bar mama has turned her into a sharp woman. But she has a short temper and often feels tired.

Resistances - drunk, fear, charm and silence.

Prone to - anger and sleep.

27.2:
Joon-gi Han's extensive training in covert operations have given him a tactical edge. However, he stays away from spicy food and alcohol.

Resistances - fear, charm and brainwash.

Prone to - drunk and burn.

28.2:
Zhao's rather demanding experience as the leader of Yokohama Liumang has toughened him up. Rumor has it that his sleep schedule and immune system are both not so well.

Resistances - bleeding, fear, rage and silence.

Prone to - cold and sleep.

29.2:
Eri is a sweet, caring woman who is a also hardworking clerk. But she doubts herself often.

Resistances - sleep and rage.

Prone to - fear, brainwash and silence.

1.2: This email is automatically sent to anyone who picks up a Tojo Clan Crest. I'm somewhat of an avid collector of these little treasures. The Tojo Clan was duped by the Omi Alliance and nearly destroyed not too long ago, and it seems that many of the Tojo Clan members' crests had been scattered across the country as a result. I'd hate to see those crests be used for anything wicked, so I want you to assist me with rounding them up! Once you collect a certain number of them, I'll happily trade you for some awesome prizes. All the more reason to bring them my way, wouldn't you say? I'll be in the courtyard of the Grande Blu Marino hotel, on Hamakita Park Ave. in Yokohama. I hope you'll come see me!

2.2: Thanks to my connections, I now have the privilege to send some real rough boys to those who need a little backup. Swing on by if you're interested.

3.2: Seems like a lot of enemies who drop crests have been showing up lately. Guess the Tojo Clan butted heads with more than just a few folks around town. Hunt these guys down and snag yourself some crests!

1.1: Welcome to the Final Millennium Tower
1.2: Job well done on getting to the end of your long, dangerous journey, intrepid hero! You've earned a reward, and I call it, "Final Millennium Tower"! It's an impregnable fortress, where only the strongest adversaries dwell, and it's difficult to say the least. Doesn't that sound tempting? Don't you feel like it's calling to you? If you have the confidence, head down to the Millennium Tower in Kamurocho. I'll be looking forward to meeting you at the very top! - The Manager

2.1: Welcome to the True Final Millennium Tower!
2.2: You are receiving this because you're one of the fearless fighters who beat the Final Millennium Tower. To be honest, I didn't expect anyone to actually train so hard they could defeat what I had thought to be an impregnable fortress. So, I have one last trick up my sleeve for those of you thirsting for an even tougher challenge. I call it... the True Final Millennium Tower. The Final Millennium Tower doesn't hold a candle to this baby. I put the entrance in a different place this time. If you think you have what it takes, come by the back door to the Millennium Tower in Kamurocho. I'll be looking forward to meeting you at the very top... again. - The Manager

1.2: I heard through the grapevine you escaped from the Yokohama Liumang's underground prison? Truth is, the tunnels 'round there go by the name "The Yokohama Underground Dungeon." The place is famous for harboring lots of rare Sujimon you don't see much aboveground. Rumor has it those Yokohama Liumang guys have cleared out too, so the enemies you can encounter should be different now. Tons of 'em are real tough cookies, so it's the perfect place to polish your skills or make some cash. The entrance is the same manhole you came out of when you escaped. I recommend you head inside and find yourself some rare Sujimon.

2.2: Yo. Looks like you're at the final stage. Got some good info perfect for a guy like you. So there's a manhole behind Theater Square that connects to the sewers, and it looks like it's the brand new stomping grounds for some tough guys who don't show their faces topside very much. Folks in the know call it "The Kamurocho Underground Dungeon."  Pretty good place to polish your skills before you go taking down the final boss, huh? I recommend you head inside and find yourself some rare Sujimon. I'm on your side. Don't lose, Ichiban Kasuga!
